window.DIJKSTRA_SCRIPT={START:e=>`Welcome to Dijkstra's journey! We're starting at node ${e} to find the quickest route to every other destination.`,VISITING:e=>`Visiting node ${e}. Let's look at all its neighbors to see if we can find any shortcuts.`,RELAXING:(e,t,n)=>`Checking the path to ${t}. By going through ${e}, we found a shortcut! The total distance is now ${n}.`,NO_SHORTCUT:e=>`The path to ${e} through our current node isn't shorter than what we already know. No change needed.`,PICKING_NEXT:e=>`All neighbors checked! Now, let's pick the closest unvisited node. That would be node ${e}!`,SUCCESS:()=>`We've explored every possible shortcut. Every node now has its guaranteed shortest path recorded!`},window.BELLMANFORD_SCRIPT={START:e=>`Time for Bellman-Ford! We'll perform ${e} passes over every edge to ensure we find the absolute shortest paths, even with negative values.`,PASS_START:e=>`Starting relaxation pass number ${e}. Here we go, checking every single edge on the map.`,RELAXING:(e,t,n)=>`Looking at the edge from ${e} to ${t}. Aha! We can relax this path down to a distance of ${n}.`,CYCLE_CHECK:()=>`One final pass to check for negative cycles. If a distance still drops now, we're in an infinite loop!`,CYCLE_FOUND:()=>`Wait! I found a shortcut that keeps getting shorter forever. That's a negative cycle! The math breaks here.`,SUCCESS:()=>`All passes complete. We've conquered the graph, negative edges and all!`},window.SEARCH_SCRIPT={DFS:{START:e=>`Let's dive deep into the graph using Depth First Search! We're starting at node ${e}.`,VISITING:e=>`Exploring node ${e}. We'll follow one path as deep as possible before we ever turn back!`,EXPLORING_EDGE:(e,t)=>`From ${e}, let's see where node ${t} takes us. Down the rabbit hole we go!`,BACKTRACKING:e=>`Dead end at ${e}! No new neighbors here. Let's backtrack and see if we missed any turns earlier.`,ALREADY_VISITED:e=>`We've already been to ${e}, so we don't need to go there again.`,SUCCESS:()=>`We've reached every part of the graph we could find. The deep dive is complete!`},BFS:{START:e=>`Time for Breadth First Search! We're starting at ${e} and spreading out like a ripple in a pond.`,VISITING:e=>`Visiting node node ${e}. We explore everyone at this distance before moving further away.`,ENQUEUE:e=>`Spotted node ${e}! Adding it to our queue of neighbors to visit very soon.`,ALREADY_VISITED:e=>`Node ${e} is already on our list or visited. No need to double back!`,SUCCESS:()=>`The ripples have reached every corner! We've explored the graph layer by layer.`},GREEDY:{START:(e,t)=>`Let's start Greedy Best-First Search! We want to find node ${t}, starting from ${e}. We'll always pick the node that "looks" closest to our goal.`,VISITING:(e,t)=>`Visiting node ${e}. Its estimated distance to the target is ${t.toFixed(1)}. It's our best bet right now!`,ENQUEUE:(e,t)=>`Spotted node ${e}! Its heuristic value is ${t.toFixed(1)}. Adding it to our priority list.`,TARGET_FOUND:e=>`Target ${e} reached! Greedy Search found a path by always heading straight for the goal.`,SUCCESS:()=>`Search complete! We've successfully navigated the graph using only our best guesses.`},ASTAR:{START:()=>`Welcome to A-Star Search! It's like Dijkstra, but smarter! It uses a 'Heuristic'â€”a best guess of the remaining distanceâ€”to head straight for the target.`,VISITING:(e,t,n,r)=>`Checking cell ${e}. Its total score is ${t}. That's ${n} steps taken plus a ${r} step guess to the finish line!`,RELAXING:(e,t)=>`Found a better way to reach ${e}! Its new priority score is ${t}. We're getting closer!`,TARGET_FOUND:()=>`Target spotted! A-Star has found the most efficient path by looking only where it needed to.`,SUCCESS:()=>`Pathfinding complete! We navigated the obstacles and reached our goal with minimal effort.`},PAGERANK:{START:()=>`Welcome to the PageRank Algorithm! We're measuring the "importance" of each node. Think of every link as a vote of confidence.`,ITERATION_START:e=>`Starting iteration ${e}. Let's see how the importance flows through the network!`,FLOW:(e,t,n)=>`Node ${e} is sharing its rank with ${t}, sending ${n.toFixed(3)} units of importance along the link.`,DAMPING:()=>`Applying the Damping Factor. This represents a "random surfer" who might jump to any page at random, keeping the math stable.`,CONVERGED:()=>`The scores have stabilized! We've found the true hierarchy of importance in our graph.`,SUCCESS:()=>`PageRank complete! The nodes with the most links from other important nodes have risen to the top.`},FLOYD_WARSHALL:{START:()=>`Welcome to the Floyd-Warshall algorithm! We're going to find the shortest path between every single pair of nodes simultaneously.`,PHASE:e=>`Phase ${e}: Let's see if we can find shorter routes by using node ${e} as an intermediate "stepping stone."`,UPDATING:(e,t,n,r,i)=>`Checking path from ${e} to ${t}. Going through ${n} gives us a distance of ${i.toFixed(1)}, which is better than our current knowledge. Updating matrix!`,SUCCESS:()=>`All pairs shortest paths calculated! The distance matrix is now complete and optimized.`},GRAPH_COLORING:{START:e=>`Let's color this graph using only ${e} colors! Our goal is to ensure no two connected nodes share the same hue.`,TRY_COLOR:(e,t)=>`Attempting to paint node ${e} with ${t}. Checking for conflicts...`,CONFLICT:(e,t,n)=>`Conflict detected! Both ${e} and ${t} would have the color ${n}. This won't work.`,BACKTRACK:e=>`No valid colors left for node ${e}. Let's backtrack and change a previous choice!`,SUCCESS:()=>`Graph perfectly colored! We've solved the puzzle without any adjacent nodes clashing.`},MAP_COLORING:{START:()=>`Welcome to the Map Coloring challenge! Based on the Four Color Theorem, any planar map can be colored with just four colors so that no touching regions share a color.`,TRY_REGION:(e,t)=>`Attempting to shade region ${e} with ${t}. Checking all neighboring borders...`,CONFLICT:(e,t,n)=>`Boundary conflict! Region ${e} and ${t} share a border and cannot both be ${n}.`,SUCCESS:()=>`Map complete! Every territory is distinct, and all boundaries are respected using a minimal palette.`}};